    "40": {
      "play": "them? What prodigal portion have I spent that I",
      "notes": [
        "prodigall portion] This may be a case of prolepsis; that is, ‘what portion have I prodigally spent;’ thus also ‘the gentle condition of blood’ in line 46, ‘the condition of gentle blood,’ or as in ‘two weak evils, age and hunger,’ II, vii, 138, and elsewhere. Schmidt’s Lexicon (p. 1420) gives many instances. Or, since the allusion is so clear to the Parable, it might be possibly the genitive of apposition, and equivalent to ‘what prodigal’s portion have I spent;’ in this case the two words should be joined by a hyphen.—ED."
      ]
    },
