    "136": {
      "play": "Therefore, out of my love to you, I came hither to",
      "notes": [
        "shall] Abbott, § 315: That is, must, will have to. Wright refers to V, i, 14. [See also II, iv, 92.]",
        "withall] ABBOTT, § 196: Sometimes this is understood after ‘withal,’ so that it means with all this, and is used adverbially: ‘So glad of this as they, I cannot be, Who are surprised withal’—Temp. III, i, 93, i. e. surprised with, or at, this. Here, however, perhaps, and elsewhere certainly, with means in addition to, and ‘with-all (this)’ means besides; as in, ‘I must have liberty withal,’ II, vii, 51 [of this present play, and also in ‘Marry, do, to make sport withal,’ in I, ii, 26.] But [in the present line] there is no meaning of besides and ‘withal’ means therewith, with it."
      ]
