    "40": {
      "play": "makes very ill-favoredly.",
      "notes": [
        "illfavouerdly] Capell (i, 55): Alter’d by the four latter moderns [i. e. Pope, Theobald, Hanmer, Warburton] into ill-favoured; in order, as may be suppos’d, to make the antithesis the rounder. But how if that roundness was dislik’d by the Poet, as thinking it destructive of the ease of his dialogue? yet this he might think, and with great reason. Collier (ed. ii): Strictly speaking, Fortune does not make the honest ‘ill-favouredly,’ but ill-favoured; and the adverbial. termination is erased in the (MS)."
      ]
