    "79": {
      "play": "honor, for he never had any, or if he had, he had",
      "notes": [
        "forsworn] Boswell: The same joke [‘such as it is’—Wright] is found in the old play of Damon and Pithias: ‘I have taken a wise oath on him, have I not, trow ye? To trust such a false knave upon his honesty? As he is an honest man (quoth you?) he may bewray all to the king, And break his oath for this never a whit.’ [Ed. Boswell's note is not found in Malone's own text; it is introduced by Boswell in the Variorum of 1821. Wright suggests that the jest lies in the ambiguity of the word \"forsworn,\" which may mean \"perjured\" or merely \"having sworn to do something.\""
      ]
