    "95": {
      "play": "CELIA: Which he will put on us as pigeons feed their",
      "notes": [
        "put on vs] I doubt the need of analysing here the exact meaning of 'put,' or of citing other passages where it is to be found. Its special meaning is plainly, almost too plainly, conveyed by Celia's simile, which is distended to its fullest extent by the simile. It is Greek, not English, to emphasize the preposition in \"put on.\"—Wright.]"
      ]
    },
