    "130": {
      "play": "ROSALIND: Alas!",
      "notes": [
        "Alas] COWDEN-CLARKE: It is often by such apparently slight touches as these that Shakespeare depicts the moral perfection of his characters and gives them their crowning charm. By this single word he shows us Rosalind pausing in the full career of her sportive word-bandying, struck with pity for the poor old father’s grief. His women are always true women; not mere heedless, heartless wits, but witty from the very depths of their sweet and sensitive natures."
      ]
    },
    "131": {
      "play": "TOUCHSTONE: But what is the sport, monsieur, that the",
      "notes": []
    },
    "132": {
      "play": "ladies have lost?",
      "notes": []
    },
    "133": {
      "play": "LE BEAU: Why, this that I speak of.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "134": {
      "play": "TOUCHSTONE: Thus men may grow wiser every day. It is",
      "notes": []
    },
    "135": {
      "play": "the first time that ever I heard breaking of ribs was",
      "notes": []
    },
    "136": {
