      "notes": [
        "The comma at the close of the preceding line led Capell to suppose that the sentence was not complete; he thereupon supplied the omission (see Textual Notes), and thus justified the addition in his notes: ‘Which circumstance [the comma after ‘company’] alone indicates an omission; but it further appears from the sense, if a little attended to: For what great crime is it, that Jaques must be woo’d for his company? but that he makes his friends woo it, and won’t let them have it after all, is an accusation of some weight. The words now inserted carry this charge.’"
