    "40": {
      "play": "JAQUES: O worthy fool!—One that hath been a courtier,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "41": {
      "play": "And says “If ladies be but young and fair,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "42": {
      "play": "They have the gift to know it.” And in his brain,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "43": {
      "play": "Which is as dry as the remainder biscuit",
      "notes": [
        "drie] WRIGHT: In the physiology of Shakespeare’s time a dry brain accompanied slowness of apprehension and a retentive memory. We read in Batman uppon Bartholome, fol. 37, b, ‘Good disposition of the braine and euill is knowne by his deedes, for if the. substance of the braine be soft, thinne, and cleere: it receiueth lightly the feeling & printing of shapes, and lykenses of thinges. He that hath such a braine is swift, and good of perseverance and teaching. When it is contarye, the braine is not softe; eyther if he be troubled, he that hath such a braine receiueth slowly the feeling and printing of thinges: But neuertheless when hee hath taken and receiued them, he keepeth them long in minde. And that is signe and token of drinesse, as fluribility & forgetting is token of moisiure, as Haly sayth.’ See Tro. & Cress. I, iii, 329.",
        "bisket] BOSWELL: So in Jonson’s Every Man Out of his Humour [Induction]: ‘And, now and then, breaks a dry biscuit jest, Which,’ &c."
      ]
    },
    "44": {
      "play": "After a voyage, he hath strange places crammed",
      "notes": [
        "places] DELIUS: That is, strange passages from books, remarkable citations. SCHMIDT (p. 455): This interpretation of Delius’s must be left undecided; no parallel example in Shakespeare occurs to me. WRIGHT: Topics or subjects of discourse. Compare Bacon, Advancement of Learning, ii, 13, §7: ‘Ancient writers of rhetoric do give it in precept, that. pleaders should have the places, whereof they have most continual use, ready handled in all the variety that may be.’ NEIL: A scholastic phrase for stock arguments, ideas, topics—Loci communes. ROLFE: That is, odd corners. Wright’s explanation as ‘topics or subjects.of discourse’ does not suit so well with ‘cramm’d.’ [There can be no doubt, I think, that Bacon uses the word as Wright has exactly defined it. In § 9, Bacon says: ‘The other part of invention, which I term suggestion, doth assign and direct us to certain marks or places, which may excite our mind to return and produce such knowledge as it hath formerly collected, to the end we may make use thereof;’ which is very nearly in Jaques’s exact phrase a ‘place, cramm’d with observation.’ Again, ‘I do receive particular topics, of invention, as places or directions of invention and inquiry in every particular knowledge, as things of great use.’—S 10. DR JOHNSON, in his Dictionary, gives as one of ‘the definitions of ‘Place,’ ‘a passage in writing,’ but under the definition ‘separate room’ he cites as an example the present phrase of Jaques. That Delius’s, Wright’s, and Neil’s interpretation is correct is shown by the rest of the sentence: these strange subjects the fool ‘vents in mangled forms.’ It is not easy to see how ‘separate rooms’ or ‘odd corners’ could be either vented or mangled.—ED.]"
      ]
    },
    "45": {
      "play": "With observation, the which he vents",
      "notes": [
        "observation] To be pronounced as five syllables. This dissolution, as it is called, of the -tion is almost universal at the end of a line, but it is comparatively rare in the body of the line. See Walker, Vers. p. 230."
      ]
    },
    "46": {
      "play": "In mangled forms. O, that I were a fool!",
      "notes": []
    },
    "47": {
      "play": "I am ambitious for a motley coat.",
      "notes": [
        "ambitious] WRIGHT: This word, as would appear from the word ‘suit’ in the next speech of Jaques, is here used with something of the meaning of the Latin ambitiosus, going about as a candidate."
      ]
