    "92": {
      "play": "Why then my taxing like a wild goose flies",
      "notes": [
        "any. man But] Another trifling variation in different copies of the First Folio. The Reprint of 1807, Staunton’s Photo-lithograph, and my copy place the period after ‘any.’ Booth’s Reprint, and the copy used by the Cambridge Editors, place it after ‘man.’—ED.",
        "Of . . . of] ABBOTT, § 407: Where the verb is at some distance from the preposition with which it is connected, the preposition is frequently repeated for the sake of clearness. See line 146 below, 'the Sceane Wherein we play in.' [There is the same idiom in Greek and in Latin.—Ed.]"
      ]
    },
