      "notes": []
    },
    "113": {
      "play": "What would you have? Your gentleness shall force",
      "notes": [
        "and] ABBOTT, § 100: I pray you may perhaps be understood after this word, implied in the imperative ‘let.’ DYCE (ed. iii): Probably (as Mr Lettsom remarks), an error caused by ‘and’ occurring twice in the next line: qy. so? WRIGHT: For this use of ‘and’ in the sense of ‘and so’ or ‘and therefore,’ see below, line 142, and Temp. I, ii, 186: ‘‘Tis a good dulness, And give it way.’"
      ]
    },
    "114": {
      "play": "More than your force move us to gentleness.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "115": {
      "play": "ORLANDO: I almost die for food, and let me have it.",
      "notes": []
