    "158": {
      "play": "Thus Rosalind of many parts",
      "notes": [
        "Wright: Shakespeare may have remembered the story of Zeuxis as told by Pliny (xxxx, 9, trans. Holland), ‘that when hee should make a table with a picture for the Agrigentines, to be set up in the temple of Iuno Lacinia, at the charges of the citie, according to a vow that they had made, hee would neédes see all the maidens of the citie, naked; and from all that companie he chose five of the fairest to take out as from severall patterns, whatsoeer hee liked best in any of them; and of all the lovely parts of those five, to make one bodie of incomparable beautie.’"
      ]
