    "164": {
      "play": "ROSALIND, as Ganymede  O most gentle Jupiter, what",
      "notes": [
        "Iupiter] Spedding’s emendation, pulpitier, adopted by the Cambridge Editors and by Dyce in his Second Edition, but abandoned in his Third, is plausible and alluring. It is the word of all words to introduce the train of thought that follows, with which ‘Jupiter’ has no connection. This addition of an -er to a noun in order to change it to an agent, like ‘moraler’ in Othello, ‘justicer’ in Lear, &c., is, as we all know, thoroughly Shakespearian. Moreover ‘Jupiter’ is not printed in Italics as though it were a proper name, to which Wright calls attention, and as it is printed in the only other place where it is used in this play, II, iv, 3; which adds to the likelihood that it is here a misprint. All these considerations are clamorous for Spedding’s pulpitier. But, on the other hand the text is clear without it; once before Rosalind has appealed to ‘Jupiter,’ and to use this mouth-filling oath, which is ‘not dangerous,’ may have been one of her characteristics, as certainly the use of expletives in general is. Although ‘Jupiter’ is not elsewhere printed in Roman, yet ‘Jove’ is, and in this very scene, line 231; and so also is ‘Judas’ in III, iv, 10. Pulpiter can mean pulpit. Pulpiter is not to be found in Halliwell or Wright, but it is in Nares, who gives only the present passage. W. A. Wright tells me, however, that it occurs at least four times in Massinger (see Glossary), and it is to be found in Ben Jonson, and other dramatists. It is clearly a contemptuous word; on t"
      ]
    },
