    "224": {
      "play": "CELIA: It is young Orlando, that tripped up the wrestler’s",
      "notes": [
        "Orlando] LADY MARTIN (p. 418): Celia answers, and this time gravely, for Rosalind’s emotion shows her this is no jesting matter. Oh happiness beyond belief, oh rapture inexpressible! The tears at this point always welled up to my eyes and my whole body trembled. If hitherto Rosalind had any doubt as to the state of her own heart, from this moment she can have none. Finding how she is overcome at the bare idea of his being near, the thought flashes on her: ‘Alas, the day! what shall I do with my doublet and hose?’ but Celia has seen him, he perhaps has seen Celia, and that perplexing thought is put aside in the eagerness to learn full particulars about her lover."
      ]
