    "237": {
      "play": "CELIA: You must borrow me Gargantua’s mouth first.",
      "notes": [
        "Gargantuas] GREY (i, 181): Alluding to Gargantua’s swallowing five pilgrims, with their pilgrims’ staves, in a salad. [Rabelais, Bk. I, chap. xxxviii.] JOHNSON: Rosalind requires nine questions to be answered in one word. Celia tells her that a word of such magnitude is too big for any mouth but that of Gargantua, the giant of Rabelais. STEEVENS: It appears from the Stationers’ Registers that in 1592 [April 6—Wright; vol. ii, p. 607, ed. Arber] was published ‘Gargantua his prophesie.’ And in 1594 [Dec. 4—Wright; vol. ii, p. 667, ed. Arber] ‘A booke entituled, the historie of Gargantua,’ &c. The book of Gargantua is likewise mentioned by Laneham in his letter from Kenilworth, 1575. HALLIWELL: Although there had been no English translation of Rabelais in Shakespeare’s time, yet it is evident from several notices that a chap-book history of Gargantua was very popular in this country in the sixteenth century. [Hereupon Halliwell gives several of these notices and other references. See Text. Notes for the misspelling started among the Editors by Pope.—ED.] WRIGHT: Cotgrave gives: ‘Gargantua. Great throat. Rab.’"
      ]
    },
    "238": {
      "play": "’Tis a word too great for any mouth of this age’s size.",
      "notes": []
