    "363": {
      "play": "love. I have heard him read many lectures against it,",
      "notes": [
        "there] Allen (MS): That is, at the court, implied in ‘courtship.’",
        "Lectors] White: This is one of the many evidences that the English of Shakespeare's time has been remarkably preserved, even in sound, by the inhabitants of New England. Throughout the Eastern States, even among a large proportion of those who are ‘inland-bred and know some culture,’ lecture is pronounced lectur. Wright: In the same way in Bacon’s Advancement of Learning, 1605, p. 30, ‘verdure is spelt “verdor.”’"
      ]
