    "392": {
      "play": "not; an unquestionable spirit, which you have not; a",
      "notes": [
        "vnquestionable] CHAMIER: Unwilling to be conversed with. M. MASON: So in [III, iv, 34] Rosalind says she had ‘much question’ with the Duke. And in V, iv, 165, the Duke was converted after ‘some question with an old religious man.’ In both places, ‘question’ means discourse or conversation. [For many more instances, see Schmidt, s. v. ‘Question,’ the noun and the verb, White refers to ‘Thou com’st in such a questionable shape,’—Ham. I, iv, 43, where the word is used in exactly the same sense; that is, thou com’st in a shape so proper to be questioned, and yet this line is often quoted as if ‘questionable’ meant ‘suspicious.’]"
      ]
    },
    "393": {
