    "404": {
      "play": "ROSALIND, as Ganymede  Me believe it? You may as",
      "notes": [
        "Me beleeue it] Keightley’s text reads ‘Make me believe it,’ and in a note (Exp. 160) he says: ‘Surely the passage thus gains not only in metre, but in spirit.’ [This is the second time (see line 84 above) that Keightley in a prose passage appeals to the needs of metre. I suppose that he assumes all of Shakespeare's prose to be metric prose, and he therein comes near the truth. I dare not say how flat his present emendation strikes me. 'Me believe it!' is absolute Rosalind; just as, afterwards, she says 'you a lover!'—Ed.]"
      ]
    },
