    "201": {
      "play": "so, come, death. Two o’clock is your hour?",
      "notes": [
        "your howre] Lady Martin (p. 429): This is to be ‘full of tears;’ and when she has put a pang into her lover’s heart by this semblance of reproachful grief, she suddenly floods it with delight by turning to him her face radiant with smiles, and saying, ‘Two o’clock’s your hour!’ This is to be ‘full of smiles,’ and the charm so works upon him that we see he has lost the consciousness that it is the boy Ganymede, and not his own Rosalind, that is before him, as he answers, ‘Ay, sweet Rosalind.’ And she, too, in her parting adjuration to him, comes nearer than she has ever done before to letting him see what is in her heart."
      ]
    },
    "202": {
