    "47": {
      "play": "bid the Duke to the nuptial. But O, how bitter a",
      "notes": [
        "Nuptiall] WRIGHT: The plural form, which is now the prevailing one, is used only twice by Shakespeare: in Per. V, iii, 80 and in Oth. II, ii, 9. In the latter passage the Ff have the singular, while the Qq read nuptialls. [In Mid. N. D. V, i, 75, the First Folio has the singular, while the three later Ff have the plural, as noted by Schmidt.]"
      ]
    },
