    "4": {
      "play": "AUDREY: I do desire it with all my heart, and I hope it is",
      "notes": []
    },
    "5": {
      "play": "no dishonest desire to desire to be a woman of the",
      "notes": [
        "dishonest] As we have had ‘honest’ in the sense of chaste in I, ii, 38; III, ii, 15, so here ‘dishonest’ means unchaste. WRIGHT: In ‘the character of the persons’ prefixed to Ben Jonson’s Every Man out of his Humour, Fallace is described: ‘She dotes as perfectly upon the courtier, as her husband doth on her, and only wants the face to be dishonest.’"
      ]
    },
    "6": {
      "play": "world.",
      "notes": [
        "world] STEEVENS: To go to the world is to be married. So in Much Ado, II, i, 331: ‘Thus goes every one to the world but I. . . . I may sit in a corner and cry beigh-ho for a husband!’ WHITIER: So also in All’s Well, I, iii, 20: ‘If I may have your Ladyship’s good will to go to the world.’ [Dyce defines it ‘to commence housekeeper,’ which is good as a hint of what, it may be presumed, is the origin of the phrase: when a young couple married and set up for themselves, they really entered the world and its ways for the first time.—ED.]"
      ]
    },
    "7": {
      "play": "Enter two Pages.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "8": {
      "play": "Here come two of the banished duke’s pages.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "9": {
      "play": "FIRST PAGE: Well met, honest gentleman.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "10": {
      "play": "TOUCHSTONE: By my troth, well met. Come, sit, sit, and",
      "notes": []
    },
    "11": {
      "play": "a song.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "12": {
      "play": "SECOND PAGE: We are for you. Sit i’ th’ middle.",
      "notes": [
        "sit i’th middle] DINGELSTEDT (p. 234): This is clearly a reference to an old English proverb [Sprichwort]: ‘hey diddle diddle, fool in the middle.’ [See Roffe’s note below, on line 16.]"
      ]
    },
    "13": {
