        "clap into’t] SCHMIDT: To enter upon, to begin with alacrity and briskness. Thus, Meas. for Meas. IV, iii, 43: ‘I would desire you to clap into your prayers; for God’s sake, and the King’s, let us clap into prayer.’ BACON (Hen. VII., p. 226, ed. 1629): ‘He clappeth a preamble to the application.’"
      ]
