    "37": {
      "play": "DUKE SENIOR: I do remember in this shepherd boy",
      "notes": []
    },
    "38": {
      "play": "Some lively touches of my daughter’s favor.",
      "notes": [
        "touches] CALDECOTT: That is, traits. See ‘the touches dearest priz’d.’—III, ii, 151. WRIGHT: As Orlando does not recognise Rosalind in her disguise, it is not surprising that her father fails to do so. But his curiosity is excited, and the inquiries which must certainly have followed upon Orlando’s speech are checked by the entry of Touchstone and Audrey."
      ]
    },
    "39": {
      "play": "ORLANDO: My lord, the first time that I ever saw him",
      "notes": []
    },
    "40": {
      "play": "Methought he was a brother to your daughter.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "41": {
      "play": "But, my good lord, this boy is forest-born",
      "notes": []
    },
    "42": {
      "play": "And hath been tutored in the rudiments",
      "notes": [
        "desperate] ALLEN (MS): Magical studies (sorcery, &c.) were supposed to be pursued by men who had made a league with the Devil, and who had, therefore, already despaired of, or renounced, their salvation; that is, they would not, unless they had already come to despair of their salvation, have made a league with the Enemy of mankind. Cf. Friar Bacon, for the union of ‘religion’ and magic. Observe, too, this is Orlando’s statement; Rosalind says the ‘magician was most profound in his art, and yet not damnable.’—V, ii, 62. [Prospero, in the Epilogue to The Tempest, says, as a magician, that his ‘ending is despair.’ Schmidt interprets it as ‘forbidden by law,’ which is, I think, far afield.—Ed.]"
      ]
    },
    "43": {
      "play": "Of many desperate studies by his uncle,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "44": {
      "play": "Whom he reports to be a great magician",
      "notes": []
    },
    "45": {
      "play": "Obscurèd in the circle of this forest.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "46": {
      "play": "Enter Touchstone and Audrey.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "47": {
      "play": "JAQUES: There is sure another flood toward, and these",
      "notes": [
        "toward] Compare ‘O proud Death, What feast is toward in thine eternal cell.’—Ham. V, ii, 375."
      ]
    },
    "48": {
      "play": "couples are coming to the ark. Here comes a pair of",
      "notes": []
    },
    "49": {
      "play": "very strange beasts, which in all tongues are called",
      "notes": [
        "verie strange] WARBURTON: What ‘strange beasts’! and yet such as have a name in all languages! Noah’s ark is here alluded to; into which the clean beasts entered by sevens, and the unclean by two, male and female. It is plain then that Shakespeare wrote ‘a pair of unclean beasts,’ which is highly humorous. JOHNSON: ‘Strange beasts’ are only what we call odd animals. WHITE: There were female jesters as well as male, and it is possible that there may be here an allusion to that custom,—Audrey being whimsically supposed by Jaques to have assumed the profession as well as the station of her husband. Else why does he call them a pair of Fools?"
      ]
    },
    "50": {
      "play": "fools.",
      "notes": [
        "fooles] Another variation in the old copies. The CAM. ED. here records foler in F1. In my copy it is fooles.—ED."
      ]
    },
    "51": {
      "play": "TOUCHSTONE: Salutation and greeting to you all.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "52": {
      "play": "JAQUES, to Duke  Good my lord, bid him welcome.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "53": {
      "play": "This is the motley-minded gentleman that I have so",
      "notes": []
    },
    "54": {
      "play": "often met in the forest. He hath been a courtier, he",
      "notes": []
    },
    "55": {
      "play": "swears.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "56": {
      "play": "TOUCHSTONE: If any man doubt that, let him put me to",
      "notes": []
    },
    "57": {
      "play": "my purgation. I have trod a measure. I have flattered",
      "notes": []
    },
    "58": {
      "play": "a lady. I have been politic with my friend,",
      "notes": []
    },
    "59": {
      "play": "smooth with mine enemy. I have undone three",
      "notes": []
    },
    "60": {
      "play": "tailors. I have had four quarrels, and like to have",
      "notes": [
        "measure] MALONE: Touchstone, to prove that he has been a courtier, particularly mentions a ‘measure,’ because it was a very stately, solemn dance. REED: ‘Measures’ were performed at court, and at public entertainments of the societies of law and equity at their halls, on particular occasions. It was formerly not deemed inconsistent with propriety even for the gravest persons to join in them; and accordingly at the revels which were celebrated at the Inns of Court it has not been unusual for the first characters in the law to become performers in treading the measures. See Dugdale’s Origines Juridiciales. Sir John Davies, in his poem called Orchestra, 1622, describes them [concluding with]: ‘Yet all the feet wherein these measures go, Are only spondees, solemn, grave, and slow.’ CHAPPELL (p. 626): The ‘measure’ was a grave and solemn dance, with slow and measured steps, like the minuet. To tread a measure was the usual term, like to walk a minuet. [Young Lord Lockinvar has made us familiar enough with the phrase.—ED.]"
      ]
    },
    "61": {
      "play": "fought one.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "62": {
      "play": "JAQUES: And how was that ta’en up?",
      "notes": [
        "tane] CALDECOTT: That is, made up. Touchstone presently says, an if did it once, ‘when seven justices could not take up a quarrel.’",
        "WEISS (p. 116): We see Touchstone’s good sense, too, in the scene where he brings his wife into the Duke’s company, with such an air of self-possession mixed with a pleased sense that she is his best joke at the punctilio of fashionable life."
      ]
    },
    "63": {
      "play": "TOUCHSTONE: Faith, we met and found the quarrel was",
      "notes": []
    },
    "64": {
      "play": "upon the seventh cause.",
      "notes": [
        "was vpon] JOHNSON: It is apparent from the sequel that we must read, ‘the quarrel was not upon the seventh cause.’ MALONE: By ‘the seventh cause’ Touch stone, I apprehend, means the lie seven times removed; i. e. ‘the retort courteous,’ which is removed seven times (counted backwards) from the lie direct, the last and most aggravated species of lie. See the subsequent note on line 72."
      ]
    },
    "65": {
      "play": "JAQUES: How “seventh cause”?—Good my lord, like",
      "notes": []
    },
    "66": {
      "play": "this fellow.",
      "notes": [
        "like] CRAIK (note on ‘is like.’—Jul. Cas. I, ii, 175): This form of expression is not quite, but nearly, gone out. ROLFE: It is still vulgarly used, at least in New England."
      ]
    },
    "67": {
      "play": "DUKE SENIOR: I like him very well.",
      "notes": []
    },
    "68": {
      "play": "TOUCHSTONE: God ’ild you, sir. I desire you of the like. I",
      "notes": [
        "God’ild you!] See III, iii, 69."
      ]
